---
const loopSteps = [
  'Define work',
  'Route context',
  'Choose workflow',
  'Run in the right mode',
  'Review output',
  'Keep what matters',
];

const layerItems = [
  {
    label: 'Repos',
    body: 'Source material that matters. Real files, real history, real ownership.',
  },
  {
    label: 'Tasks',
    body: 'Scoped intent and what done means before execution begins.',
  },
  {
    label: 'Methods',
    body: 'Prompts and skills that turn good approaches into reusable workflow.',
  },
  {
    label: 'Services',
    body: 'Search, state, notifications, forge, and observability that keep the loop durable.',
  },
  {
    label: 'Review',
    body: 'PRs and artifacts that let the human decide what becomes real.',
  },
];

const trustItems = [
  'Bounded execution over vague autonomy',
  'Search before browse',
  'Reviewable outputs only',
  'Private by default service exposure',
  'Recoverable systems with receipts',
];
---

<div class="essay-page what-page">
  <section class="page-hero-note-grid">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Foundations</p>
      <h1 class="page-display-title">What GalexC is</h1>
      <p class="page-lede">
        GalexC is a personal AI operating environment built for real bounded work.
        Not a chatbot, not a prompt bundle, and not a demo stack. It combines durable
        context, explicit methods, real tools, background execution, and reviewable
        outputs so useful work can happen under clear operational constraints. In the
        simplest terms, it is professional-grade personal AI.
      </p>
    </div>
    <ul class="page-note-list">
      <li>Not a chatbot</li>
      <li>Not a demo stack</li>
      <li>Not autonomous theater</li>
      <li>A personal AI operating environment</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="page-module page-module-panel">
    <div class="module-heading-row">
      <p class="eyebrow">Operating loop</p>
      <p class="page-caption">The product is the loop, not a single assistant.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="loop-diagram">
      {
        loopSteps.map((step, index) => (
          <>
            <div class="loop-step">{step}</div>
            {index < loopSteps.length - 1 && <div class="loop-connector" aria-hidden="true"></div>}
          </>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-grid-two">
    <article class="page-module page-module-panel mode-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Interactive mode</p>
      <h2>Think live.</h2>
      <p>
        Interactive sessions are where work takes shape. They clarify scope, test
        assumptions, search the right context, and tighten the brief until the task is
        safe to hand off.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="page-module page-module-panel mode-card mode-card-firm">
      <p class="eyebrow">Dispatch mode</p>
      <h2>Execute asynchronously.</h2>
      <p>
        Dispatch takes on work that is already bounded well enough to run in the
        background. The result comes back as a PR, artifact, or report that can be
        reviewed at the right moment.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="page-module">
    <div class="module-heading-row">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Built from durable primitives</p>
        <h2 class="page-section-title">More operating environment than assistant</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="page-caption">
        The leverage comes from composition, not from pretending one model is the whole
        product.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="layer-stack">
      {
        layerItems.map((item) => (
          <div class="layer-stack__item">
            <p class="layer-stack__label">{item.label}</p>
            <p>{item.body}</p>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-grid-two page-grid-two-wide-right">
    <article class="page-module">
      <p class="eyebrow">Why it matters</p>
      <h2 class="page-section-title">A system that compounds</h2>
      <p>
        Useful context should accumulate instead of dissolving into scrollback. Methods
        should become reusable. Async work should return with enough structure that
        review becomes short and trust becomes earned. GalexC exists to help one person
        think better, execute faster, preserve continuity, and build real leverage
        without giving up ownership.
      </p>
    </article>
    <aside class="page-module page-module-panel trust-panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Strong boundaries</p>
      <ul class="trust-panel__list">
        {trustItems.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </section>
</div>
